# Ligamentum Nuchae

> The **ligamentum nuchae** is a large, triangular fibroelastic ligament extending from the external occipital protuberance to the spinous process of C7. It is a continuation of the supraspinous ligament in the cervical region and serves as a muscle attachment site.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Proximal** — External occipital protuberance (occiput)
- **Distal** — Spinous processes of C1–C7; continuous with [[Supraspinous Ligament]] below
- **Muscle attachments** — [[Trapezius]], Splenius capitis, Rhomboid minor attach to it
- **Related structures** — [[Cervical Vertebrae]], [[Skull]]

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Cervical stability** — Passive support for the head; limits cervical flexion
- **Calcification** — Can calcify with age; seen on lateral cervical X-ray
- **Quadruped analogy** — Highly developed in grazing animals (e.g., ox) to support head without muscular effort

